  <h1>Whistleblower Misconceptions</h1>
  <h2>"I need to be an employee of the company I'm reporting."</h2>
  <p>False. SEC and CFTC programs accept tips from anyone with original information — competitors, customers, investors, or independent analysts. You don't need to be an insider.</p>
  <h2>"If I report internally first, I lose my whistleblower status."</h2>
  <p>Not necessarily. Under SEC rules, internal reporters may preserve their status as original source if the company later reports the same information to the SEC, and they can still qualify for an award based on the information they provided.</p>
  <h2>"Whistleblower protections only apply if you win an award."</h2>
  <p>Anti-retaliation protections under Dodd-Frank apply when you report to the SEC — regardless of whether an award is ultimately paid. The protection is triggered by the act of reporting, not the outcome.</p>
  <h2>"My information isn't valuable because regulators probably know about it."</h2>
  <p>Agencies receive tens of thousands of complaints and have limited investigative bandwidth. Specific, original information about a concrete violation is valuable even if regulators have some general awareness of an issue.</p>
  <h2>"I should wait until I have more evidence."</h2>
  <p>Filing a preliminary tip establishes your submission date, which is critical for award priority. You can supplement your tip later. Waiting risks another person submitting the same information first — programs generally pay only one award per enforcement action.</p>
</BaseLayout>
